Geospatial data visualisation in R: bonus challenge 2 - leaflet + crosstalk

2023-08-31

Note: only the knitted document (html file) can correctly show the solution of the third exercise.

Libraries:

library(crosstalk)
library(leaflet)
library(htmltools)
library(DT)
library(sf)

Bonus challenge 1

Prepare data

Read and prepare data (same code as provided in 20230831_challenges.R):

# n_moths
n_moths <- readr::read_csv("./data/20230831/20230831_n_moths.txt")
## Rows: 395 Columns: 2
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): TAG
## dbl (1): n
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
# UTM1km cells of Pajottenland
utm1_pajottenland <- sf::st_read(
  "./data/20230831/20230831_utm1km_Pajottenland.gpkg"
)
## Reading layer `20230831_utm1km_Pajottenland' from data source 
##   `C:\Users\damiano_oldoni\Documents\GitHub\coding-club\data\20230831\20230831_utm1km_Pajottenland.gpkg' 
##   using driver `GPKG'
## Simple feature collection with 538 features and 3 fields
## Geometry type: POLYGON
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: 3.877959 ymin: 50.6825 xmax: 4.432543 ymax: 50.89765
## Geodetic CRS:  WGS 84
# join data
n_moths <- utm1_pajottenland %>%
  dplyr::left_join(n_moths, by = "TAG")

From polygons to points

Generate centroids of the UTM 1x1km cells:

n_moths_centroids <- sf::st_centroid(n_moths)
## Warning: st_centroid assumes attributes are constant over geometries

Color palette

Crete the color palette from column n with number of moth species:

pal <- leaflet::colorNumeric(
  palette = "viridis",
  domain = n_moths$n)

Exercise 1

  1. Combine leaflet with data table via crosstalk. Unfortunately, crosstalk doesn’t support polygons at the moment (see https://github.com/rstudio/crosstalk/issues/55). So, use the leaflet map with circle markers you created in the last exercise of BONUS CHALLENGE 1. Hint: everything you are doing is html. So, use the R package DT to display the data.frame as HTML “tables”.
shared_n_moths_centroids <- crosstalk::SharedData$new(n_moths_centroids)

# create same leaflet as before but starting from new object wich allows us to
# link data to circles
map_shared_n_moths <- leaflet(shared_n_moths_centroids) %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addCircleMarkers(popup = ~htmlEscape(TAG),
                   label = ~htmlEscape(n),
                   radius = ~n/10,
                   color = ~pal(n),
                   stroke = FALSE,
                   fillOpacity = 0.5)

# create table with the data
data_table <- datatable(
  shared_n_moths_centroids,
  extensions="Scroller",
  style="bootstrap",
  class="compact",
  width="100%",
  options=list(deferRender=TRUE, scrollY=300, scroller=TRUE)
)

# combine map with table
bscols(map_shared_n_moths, data_table)

Exercise 2

Add filter slider:

filter_slider(id = "n",
              label = "Number of moth species",
              sharedData = shared_n_moths_centroids,
              column = ~n,
              step = 5,
              # start from zero to have 0 - 10 - 20 ...ticks
              min = 0,
              width = max(n_moths$n)
)
bscols(map_shared_n_moths, data_table)
